{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332894195/1930021701/0297.xml":{"full_text":"\u00ael* Bnmmsuflle Herald\n__E\u00bbtabli\u00bbhed July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter in the Postoffice\nBrownsville. Texas.\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\n_ COMPANY\nSubscription Rates\u2014Daily and Sunday (7 issues)\n0\u201c\u00ae Ymr\nSix Months .....$4 50\nThree Months.f225\nOne Month.] 75\nMEMBER OF TIIE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press Is exclusively entitled to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to It or\ntot otherwise credited in this paper, and also the\nocal news published herein.\nHarlingen Office. Reese-Wil-Mond Hotel. Phone 1020.\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas. Texas, 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo., 396 Coca Cola Building.\nChicago. I1L, Association Building.\nNew York, 350 MadUon Avenue.\nSt. Louis, 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles, Cal., Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg..\n846 S. Broadway.\nSan Francisco, Cal., 318 Kohl Building.\nHome Industries and How They\nAre Protected\nThe slogan of the republican party and the re\npublican administration that high tariffs are neces\nsary for the protection of American manufacturing,\nAmerican money and American labor.\nTexas has a vast army of small investors and wage\nworkers engaged in the petroleum industry. They\nare known as independents. They compete with for\neign labor. Foreign crude is on the free list and\nthe senate of Texas, 15 to 7, voted that the Texas\nIndependents in the oil game are not entitled to the\ntariff protection given the makers of things in the\nNorth and the East.\nThat is, the growers and independents producers of\nthings were given a legislative slap on the Jaw. There\nare 31 senators. Eight were absent. They failed to\nfigure in the voting as the record for the press was\nmace by the correspondents.\nThere is a way to avoid tackling real economic\nIssues. All a politician or lawmaker has to do is to\nyell from the housetops for law enforcement of the\n18th amendment and the Volstead act. Law en\nforcement Is to be commended, but why make it a\nsmoke screen for the purpose of avoiding the live\neconomic Issues which concern the farmers of Ameri\nca and their rapidly decaying Industry?\nThese issues cannot be choloroformed. All the sur\nface signs Indicate growers of things, the producers of\nthe important American staples, are weary of serving\nas hewers of wood and drawers of water for *he\nmakers of things and their Grundy and Watsons\nwho shape the legislation of the country.\nOrganizer! Agriculture Rebel#\n\"Organized agriculture is in rebellion against the\npending tariff bill\" reads a Washington dispatch.\nRepresentatives of seven of the levins farm organi\nzations of the United States, in an open letter ad\ndressed to members of the senate, asserted \"the pres\nent state of the senate measure would prevent a\n'estoration of a balanced agriculture\nThis followed in the wake of the departure of Pres.\nHerbert Hoover and General Publicity Agent Mark\nBuilivan to a point on the Florida coast, \"where the\nlishing is splendid\nWell* what are the members of the seven leading\nfarm organizations of the United States going to do\naboaut It in the elections this year?\nThere are 6.500.000 farmers in the 48 states.\nThey could play the devil in many western and\nnorthwestern states with the official programs and\nthe slate nominees of the G. O. P.\u2014that is, if they\nhad the nerve to strike a blow In defense of their\nown convictions and for the protection of their own\nproduct and firesides.\nWill they? They haven\u2019t to date\u2014since the close\nof the war between the states.\nA Great American Nearing\nThe End\nWilliam Howard Taft is said to be hanging on the\nbrink of the grave. If so a great and patriotic Ameri\ncan of the old school is about to pass out of the\npicture to the regret of millions.\nREGARDING SKI-JUMPING\n(Copyright, 1030, by The Associated N. rpapers.)\nDear Editor: Will you kindly toll me hov/ you -ate\nski-jumping among the activities of life? Having\nbeen viewing the news reels and rotogravure sections\nlately, I have been a little surprised to note the vast\nnumber of people engaged in this sport. 1 am a young\nman. 23 years of age, anxious to get ahead in life, out\nI am meeting with no success. Nobody seems Interest\ned in me. No one pays attention Do you think It\nis because I am not a ski-Jumper?\nWorried Reader.\n\nDear Worried: Your letter reflects the quandary\nof thousands of newspaper readers and moving pic\nture fans. Your question is timely. We are glad you\nasked. Ski-jumping is (unless the news reel and\nrotogravure editors are fooling us) one of the world\u2019s\nmajor interests. Everybody seems to be doing it, and\nit tends to make a man who never leaped across ail\nicy valley in las life feel awfully inadequate, not to\nsay silly.\nIt Is coming more and more to be realized that with\nI out ski-jumping at.Iity a youui is under a sei.oua\n1 handicap in lue, especially from Deixmbcr to April.\n11 he i.\\L^ in a country where there is any saow it\nis absolutely necessary that he j..u'.p. And even U he\nlives in a land where there is no snow or ice ne i.nd\nit essential to grasp the detail ol the sport and be\nable to discuss it, since there is a point in all con\nversations at which the subject arises.\n\nA young man who get3 about at ail with people\nwho read the papers and go to the picture houses\nwill be under a great advantage il he himself ;s a\nmaster of ski-jumping, and it means a lot to an\nolder man to be able to say \u201cI am an old ski-jumper\nmyself.\u201d If it is Impossible for you to take up ski\njumping buy. beg or borrow a pair of skates at once,\nmy boy, and attain a reasonable skill at It. It will\nhelp you socially and In business.\u201d\n\nBrokerage houses and Insurance companies are be\ncoming glutted with football, baseball and golf stars\nbut a good bond salesman who has won fame at\nski-jumping is hard to find. His services command\na premium.\n\nSki-Jumping is a character-builder. It develops\nnerve, courage, self-confidence, poise and assurance.\nA youth who has become a Grade A ski-jumper never\nagain will know that intuitive fear of falling eff a\nroof or being thrown out of college.\n\nBy all means, young man. take tm sk!-Jumping\nbefore it is too late. Everybody else lias.\nANOTHER NAME FDR TTYT MUDDLE\n\u201cMay I see Mr. Ostcrb: ura?\u201d r 1 the caller at\nthe office of one of the city\u2019s big business men.\n\u201cSorry.\u201d replied the stenographer who had been\nreading the newspapers, \u201cbut It can-: be seen just\nnow. He\u2019s in plenary senior..\u201d\nUNION. N. J., Feb. 6\u2014 v\u2014Mias Irene Franklin,\nactress, who planned last fall to establish a vacation\nhome for poor chorus girls h :c, has changed her\nmind and bought a yacht.\n\nThat for charity; And that and that!\nA census shows there are twelve Henry Fords in\nthe city of Detroit. Chicago isn't gctnng such a bad\nbreak after all.\n\nA tabloid editor\u2019s idea of complete frustration is\n'lcaruv: that a pretty gnl who was murdered left be\nhind her no photogiapho in pajamas or onc-picco\nbathing suit.\nHave you heard about the applicant who was re\nfused a druggist s license by the examining board be\ncause he couldn't slice a ham thin enough?\n\nTIMIDITY.\nThe market it is going up\nAnd stock I d quickly grab. son.\nIf I could get a guarantee\ni There'd be no word from Babson.\nTHE OLD HOME TOWN.Stanley\n'BOBBY, LET ME\nBotsreow You^\nI SLEO, WANT Tt\n\\SES HOW CLOSw\nl CAN COME to\nTHAT FEtuea\nNWlTHOUT HtTT/N\nHIM~^_\nAW GEE,YO'JT?E'\nl TOO OUO FOfe I\nCOAST in'\nWALKED1\n__y\n/>w let hit* A\nHAVE IT. eoBJ\nHE WONT j\nBREAK \\T \"y\nI SW'ttJS/\nIT LOOKS LIKE MARSHAL OTdY WALKED IS\nGETTING KITTENISH. BUT KNOWING* OTEY AS\nVMELL AS Vl\u00a3 DO, THERES PR03A3LY\nMETHOD IN HIS MADNESS\u2014 sr~ TdM3*Rcwff\nPAPE^